SIMPLE: preraphaelite
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Preraphaelite
<hw>Pre*raph"a*el*ite</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Of or
pertaining to the style called preraphaelitism; <as>as, a
<ex>preraphaelite</ex> figure; a <ex>preraphaelite</ex>
landscape.</as></def> <rj><au>Ruskin.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preraphaelite</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Preraphaelite
<hw>Pre*raph"a*el*ite</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who
favors or practices art as it was before Raphael; one who favors or
advocates preraphaelitism.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Popularly, any modern artist thought to be a
would-be restorer of early ideas or methods, as one of the German
painters often called <stype>Nazarenes</stype>, or one who paints and
draws with extreme minuteness of detail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preregnant</ent>⟦br⟧
